I thought this event was worthy of sharing....

POW/MIA Recognition EventğŸ‡ºğŸ‡¸

On Friday, September 18 from 9:00 - 10:00 a.m. the San Augustine Memorial Auxiliary Post 9313 will honor and pay our respects to the soldiers that are Prisoners of War or Missing in Action (POW/MIA's). According to National League of POWMIA Families as of July 15, 2020 there are 1,586 soldiers unaccounted for -- 99 of those soldiers are from the state of Texas.
After the recognition, the auxiliary will be providing donuts and orange juice. The event is being held on the San Augustine Square. The donuts and orange juice will be stationed right next to Texas Star Retail Store & Boutique. We would love for you to come and visit with some of our local veterans and auxiliary members. If you have any questions, please donâ€™t hesitate to contact Gina Brown at 936-201-2756 or Rachel Lester at 936-201-5374.

shared_text:
Terry Sympson
August 7 at 3:07 PM Â·

I am really excited to announce that we will be having a very special guest staying with us from August 11th til September 12th. Ernie Andrus is a WWII Veteran that we met when he was a young 91 years old and running from coast to coast in 2015. Ernie is doing it again this time he is going East to West retracing his last trip. We have the amazing honor of hosting him here at Jackson Hill to celebrate his 97th birthday on August 19th and want to invite all of you to an online National Happy Birthday song for one of the greatest of the greatest generation. Guests to the marina are welcome to meet Ernie and while we will be taking precautions Ernie has made it clear that he wants to meet people and is unafraid to shake hands and get a hug from the kids along his way. I have attached a photos from Ernie's first visit with us. To find out more about him go to www.coast2coastruns.com I will be keeping you posted.

AN AMERICAN MAIN STREET PATRIOTIC EVENT
Friday, 9-11-2020

The City of San Augustine Main Street Program and its co-sponsors will host the sixth annual â€œAn American Main Streetâ€ on Friday, Sept. 11 from 6:00 to 7:00(ish) PM on the square in downtown San Augustine. The event will remember those who gave it all on 9-11 and recognize and honor all area First Responders, Law Enforcement, Military Service Organizations, Healthcare/Emergency and Volunteer agencies county wide. The free to the public event will include a boxed dinner for folks to take home! So mark your calendars and plan to be there to express your appreciation and cheer on our responders and frontline essential workers!

San Augustine Motor Company is with Angel Eufracio.
August 3 at 12:24 PM Â·

The time has come for our summer intern to return back to campus for the fall semester. Angel has been in charge of running our social media platforms and their analytics throughout this past month, but now we watch him as he makes his way back to Texas A&M University in College Station. Angel is a member of the Corps of Cadets and will return to his outfit, Squadron 18, as a cadet Staff Sergeant. We wish him the best of luck as he tackles his junior year. The staff here at San Augustine Motor Company looks forward to seeing you again, Angel! Thank you, and good luck!!!

Although we could never be able to give the award to every deserving business at any given time, we endeavor to move the award around when we catch a glimpse of clean-up in action! Texas Historical Commission
June 18 at 3:30 PM Â·

On Friday, June 19, tune in to the ACHP - Advisory Council on Historic Preservation to hear ACHP Expert Member and CEO Chairman Robert G. Stanton talk about the legacy of Juneteenth.

Stanton, a Texan, was the first African American director of the National Park Service. He is an inspiring speaker whose life's work has been dedicated to preserving cultural and natural resources.

The interview will also be available on the ACHP YouTube channel.

Image: Stained-glass window by artist Jean Tracy, Trinity United Methodist Church, Houston.

Texas Downtown
May 5 at 10:01 AM Â·

This #GivingTuesday we ask you to consider donating to the Anice Read Fund. The Anice Read Fund is a grant fund for downtown projects and programs and available only to TDA members. The Fund is named for Texas downtown legend Anice Read, a TDA founding partner and first director of the Texas Main Street Program. While Anice passed away in 1999, this fund continues her legacy and offers gap financing to members who want to improve their downtowns. Since 2000 the Fund has distributed more than $150,000 in grants to Texas communities and nonprofits, leveraging more than $5 million in funding from other sources.
Donations can be made through the Communities Foundation of Texas' website: https://portal.cftexas.org/anice-read

April 30 at 5:12 PM Â·

The Texas Historical Commission is preparing to reopen most of our state historic sites for day-use only on Friday, May 1. We continue to encourage social distancing and other best practices to avoid spreading the virus, and we will continue to advise our customers to know and follow local, state, or federal travel restrictions and other guidance.

Starting Friday, our historic sites guidelines will include strongly encouraging visitors to wear face coverings, maintain a six-foot distance from individuals outside their party, and not gather in groups larger than five outside of the same household.

As many sites are reopening, capacity will be limited. Select sites will require reservations to be made over the phone.

Stay local and check the status of our sites before you visit: thc.texas.gov/historicsites.
